# Trust Policies

---

## 9. Why Trust Policies Exist

Suppose we create:

```
InventoryRole
```

Question:

Who is allowed to use this role?

Possible identities:

- EC2
- Lambda
- IAM User
- Another AWS Account

AWS answers this using a **Trust Policy**.

---

## 10. Beginner Explanation

Imagine a finance server room protected by a security guard.

Every visitor is asked:

> "Who are you?"

If the visitor appears on the approved list:

✅ Access granted

Otherwise:

❌ Access denied

That approved list is the Trust Policy.

---

## 11. Technical Definition

A Trust Policy defines:

> **Who is allowed to assume an IAM Role.**

It does **not** define permissions.

It only defines **who can use the role.**

---

## 12. Two Policies Every IAM Role Has

Every IAM Role contains:

```
IAM Role

├── Trust Policy

└── Permission Policy
```

These policies perform completely different jobs.

---

## 13. Trust Policy

Question answered:

> **Who can assume this role?**

Example:

```json
{
  "Principal": {
    "Service": "ec2.amazonaws.com"
  }
}
```

Meaning:

Only EC2 is trusted to assume this role.

---

## 14. Permission Policy

Question answered:

> **What can the role do after being assumed?**

Example permissions:

- Read S3
- Write CloudWatch Logs
- Write DynamoDB

---

## 15. Hotel Analogy

Security happens in two stages.

### Step 1

Reception asks:

> Are you a registered guest?

This is the **Trust Policy**.

---

### Step 2

Your room key opens:

- Your room
- Gym

But not:

- Other guest rooms
- Manager's office

This is the **Permission Policy**.

---

## 16. Policy Evaluation Flow

```
EC2
      ↓
Trust Policy

Can EC2 Assume Role?

      ↓
YES

      ↓
Temporary Credentials

      ↓
Permission Policy

What Can EC2 Do?

      ↓

Read S3
Write Logs
```

AWS first checks:

> Can this principal assume the role?

Only after that does AWS check:

> What permissions does the role have?

---

## 17. Principal

A Principal is:

> **The identity requesting access.**

Examples:

- IAM User
- IAM Role
- AWS Account
- EC2 Service
- Lambda Service
- IAM Identity Center User
- Federated Identity

---

## 18. Trust Policy Examples

### EC2

```json
{
  "Principal": {
    "Service": "ec2.amazonaws.com"
  }
}
```

Meaning:

EC2 can assume this role.

---

### Lambda

```json
{
  "Principal": {
    "Service": "lambda.amazonaws.com"
  }
}
```

Meaning:

Lambda can assume this role.

---

### Cross Account

```json
{
  "Principal": {
    "AWS": "arn:aws:iam::222222222222:root"
  }
}
```

Meaning:

AWS Account **222222222222** is trusted to assume this role.

---

## 19. Every IAM Role Needs a Trust Policy

Without a Trust Policy:

No principal is allowed to assume the role.

The role effectively becomes unusable.

---

## 20. Permission Policy vs Trust Policy

| Trust Policy | Permission Policy |
|---------------|-------------------|
| Who can assume the role? | What actions are allowed? |
| Uses Principal | Uses Actions & Resources |
| Controls access to the role | Controls access to AWS resources |

---

## 21. Production Architecture Example

Data Pipeline

```
EC2
     │
EC2S3UploadRole
     │
     ▼
S3 Bucket

--------------------------

Lambda
     │
LambdaDynamoDBRole
     │
     ▼
DynamoDB
```

Each workload receives its own dedicated IAM Role.

This follows the Principle of Least Privilege.

---

## 22. Why Separate Roles Matter

Bad Design

```
UniversalRole

↓

EC2
Lambda
Glue
ECS
```

If one workload is compromised, every permission inside the UniversalRole becomes available to the attacker.

Better Design:

- One Role per Workload

---

## 23. Another Real Data Engineering Example

```
Airflow EC2
       │
AirflowExecutionRole
       │
       ▼
Read Files From S3

----------------------

Glue Job
      │
GlueExecutionRole
      │
      ▼
Transform Data

----------------------

Redshift
      │
RedshiftCopyRole
```

Every service has its own IAM Role.

If Glue is compromised, EC2 permissions remain protected.

