# 🏢 Real-World Scenarios

## Scenario 1 — GitHub Credential Leak

> A company stored AWS Access Keys inside every EC2 server.
>
> One developer accidentally committed the credentials to GitHub.
>
> Every server's credentials became compromised.
>
> The company had to rotate hundreds of access keys.
>
> After migrating to IAM Roles:
>
> - No secrets stored on servers
> - No credential management
> - Better security
> - Easier operations

---

## Scenario 2 — Wrong Trust Policy

> Developers created an IAM Role with S3 permissions.
>
> Everything looked correct.
>
> But the Trust Policy trusted:
>
> `lambda.amazonaws.com`
>
> instead of:
>
> `ec2.amazonaws.com`
>
> Result:
>
> EC2 could not assume the role.
>
> No temporary credentials were issued.
>
> The application received Access Denied errors.

---

## Scenario 3 — Secure Lambda Architecture

Multiple Lambda Functions:

- OrderLambdaRole
- PaymentLambdaRole
- NotificationLambdaRole
- InvoiceLambdaRole

Every role trusts:

```
lambda.amazonaws.com
```

But each Permission Policy grants only the permissions needed by that function.

This follows **Least Privilege**.

---

# ⚠️ Common Mistakes & Misconfigurations

### Using IAM Users on EC2

Using Access Keys inside EC2 applications is insecure.

Use IAM Roles instead.

---

### Giving AdministratorAccess to Every Role

If an EC2 instance only uploads images to S3:

Do not grant:

- IAM permissions
- Billing
- EC2 Full Access

Grant only:

```
s3:PutObject
```

---

### Creating One Universal Role

One Role shared by EC2, Lambda, ECS, Glue, etc.

Danger:

If one service is compromised, every permission becomes compromised.

---

### Confusing Trust Policy with Permission Policy

Incorrect:

Putting S3 permissions inside the Trust Policy.

Correct:

Trust Policy:

Who can assume?

Permission Policy:

What actions are allowed?

---

### Trusting Everyone

Using:

```json
"Principal": "*"
```

This is dangerous because it may allow unintended principals to attempt to assume the role.

---

### Wrong Service Principal

Example:

EC2 Role trusts:

```
lambda.amazonaws.com
```

Result:

EC2 cannot assume the role.

---

# 🎯 Interview Angle

Common interview questions:

### What is an IAM Role?

> An IAM Role is an AWS identity that provides temporary credentials to trusted principals. It has no password or permanent access keys.

---

### Does an IAM Role have a password?

No.

---

### Does an IAM Role have permanent Access Keys?

No.

Temporary credentials are issued by AWS STS.

---

### Why are IAM Roles preferred over IAM Users for EC2?

- No permanent credentials
- Temporary credentials
- Automatic credential rotation
- Reduced credential leakage risk
- Better security

---

### What is a Trust Policy?

A Trust Policy defines which principals are allowed to assume an IAM Role.

---

### What is the difference between Trust Policy and Permission Policy?

Trust Policy:

Who can assume the role.

Permission Policy:

What actions are allowed after assuming the role.

---

### What is a Principal?

The identity requesting access.

Examples:

- IAM User
- IAM Role
- AWS Account
- AWS Service
- Federated User

